[
    {
        "content": "<p>Is there an equivalent of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=NormedAlgebra#doc\">docs#NormedAlgebra</a> where <code>ùïú</code> is a <code>NormedCommRing</code> and not a <code>NormedField</code>?</p>",
        "id": 468448228,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1725731172
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=BoundedSMul#doc\">docs#BoundedSMul</a>, but that's about it.</p>",
        "id": 468467107,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1725738697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think BoundedSMul covers precisely the use case you want</p>",
        "id": 468467638,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1725738936
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But does it work well with the norm? I'm not sure how much we have generalized.</p>",
        "id": 468469322,
        "sender_full_name": "Jireh Loreaux",
        "timestamp": 1725739686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I put a fair amount of effort into this style of generalization last year</p>",
        "id": 468470088,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1725740337
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I need something like <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=norm_smul#doc\">docs#norm_smul</a>, but without <code>Œ±</code> being a division ring. More generally, do we have anything about normed rings which aren't division rings but the norm still is multiplicative?</p>",
        "id": 468518123,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1725774379
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Presumably <code>norm_smul_le</code> isn't enough for you?</p>",
        "id": 468535587,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1725786419
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(a lot of time there is an easy proof using <code>norm_smul</code>, and a slightly more fiddly one using <code>norm_smul_le</code>)</p>",
        "id": 468535766,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1725786480
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the answer to your question is \"no\", but I also think there is some past discussion on the matter elsewhere on Zulip, which I'll link if I can find</p>",
        "id": 468535891,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1725786546
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I want to generalize <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/16597\">#16597</a>, I don't see how to do that with <code>norm_smul_le</code></p>",
        "id": 468543114,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1725790128
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How about using <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Valuation#doc\">docs#Valuation</a> ? Then you can apply the result to the rationals with the usual norm, or with the p-adic norm.</p>",
        "id": 468545236,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1725791266
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How does that work? The usual norm doesn't satisfy <code>f (x + y) ‚â§ max (f x) (f y)</code>, unless I'm missing something?</p>",
        "id": 468545628,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1725791398
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh lol yeah good point :-)</p>",
        "id": 468545902,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1725791501
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15445\">#15445</a> I introduce an <code>AlgebraNorm</code> structure and the corresponding <code>AlgebraNormClass</code>:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">structure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">AlgebraNorm</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">SeminormedCommRing</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Ring</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Algebra</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">extends</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">RingNorm</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Seminorm</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">S</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>(I know this is not exactly what you are asking for, but I am pointing it out in case it is helpful.)</p>",
        "id": 468860400,
